 a significant role for the excitation of\nthe molecular lines.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 25 Feb 2007 20:34:40 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-13"}
{"id":"astro-ph/0702671","submitter":"Laxmikant Chaware","authors":"R.K.Thakur","title":"Do Black Holes End up as Quark Stars ?","comments":"6 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  The possibility of the existence of quark stars has been discussed by several\nauthors since 1970. Recently, it has been pointed out that two putative neutron\nstars, RXJ 1856.5 - 3754 in Corona Australis and 3C58 in Cassiopeia are too\nsmall and too dense to be neutron stars; they show evidence of being quark\nstars. Apart from these two objects, there are several other compact objects\nwhich fit neither in the category of neutron stars nor in that of black holes.\nIt has been suggested that they may be quark stars.In this paper it is shown\nthat a black hole cannot collapse to a singularity, instead it may end up as a\nquark star. In this context it is shown that a gravitationally collapsing black\nhole acts as an ultrahigh energy particle accelerator, hitherto inconceivable\nin any terrestrial laboratory, that continually accelerates particles\ncomprising the matter in the black hole. When the energy \\textit{E} of the\nparticles in the black hole is $\\geq 10^{2}$GeV, or equivalently the\ntemperature \\textit{T} of the matter in the black holes is $\\geq 10^{15}$K, the\nentire matter in the black hole will be converted into quark-gluon plasma\npermeated by leptons. Since quarks and leptons are spin 1/2 particles,they are\ngoverned by Pauli's exclusion principle. Consequently, one of the two\npossibilities will occur; either Pauli's exclusion principle would be violated\nand the black hole would collapse to a singularity, or the collapse of the\nblack hole to a singularity would be inhibited by Pauli's exclusion principle,\nand the black hole would eventually explode with a mini bang of a sort. After\nexplosion, the remnant core would stabilize as a quark star.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 25 Feb 2007 21:34:59 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
